<DOC><DOCNO> AP891007-0126 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 2043EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Morocco-Rebels     10-07 0307</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Morocco-Rebels,0321</SECOND><HEAD>Rebel Attack Ignites Heaviest Fighting in Months</HEAD><BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>RABAT, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Polisario rebels in the disputed WesternSahara attacked a Moroccan defense line Saturday, setting off thebloodiest battle since the two sides declared a truce in February.   The government said 14 of its soldiers were killed and 80 rebelskilled or wounded.   A Polisario statement, which described the battle as ``murderousviolence,'' said the fighting broke out at dawn and lasted fourhours.   The statement, issued in Algeria, Algiers, claimed its fightersbreached nine miles of Morocco's defensive front and pushedgovernment forces back 15 miles.   The rebels did not say how the battle ended or give casualtyfigures. It said ``numerous'' government soldiers forces werekilled, wounded or taken prisoner.   The government reported that in addition to the 14 soldierskilled 31 troopers were wounded. It also said four rebels weretaken prisoner.   It claimed its forces repelled the attack launched south of thetown of Guelta Zemmour from Mauritanian territory.   The government said its troops captured 10 jeeps armed withmissile launchers and anti-tank rockets, and 12 Polisario vehicleswere destroyed by Moroccan air attacks.   The Western Sahara has been claimed by Morocco since Spain leftthe territory in 1975, but the Polisario has proclaimed it anindependent state.   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar has proposed aplan to hold a referendum in the mineral-rich region.   The Polisasrio guerrilla movement, once actively supported byAlgeria, has fought a mainly losing battle against about 100,000Moroccan troops in the area.   The Sahara front had been quiet, except for isolated Polisarioattacks, since the guerrillas declared a ``temporary truce'' inFebruary following King Hassan II's meeting with Polisario leadersin Marrakech.   Similar meetings had been scheduled but were canceled by theking, who called them ``pointless.''</TEXT></DOC>